INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '0a7c6941-e78b-4d5d-a959-39a97dfca5e9',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$ollama — Tokens, Context Windows, and Sampling Parameters That Actually Matter$escape$,
  $escape$Every ollama model has a fixed context window — the maximum tokens it can process in a single request. llama3.2 defaults to 2048 tokens; mistral to 4096. Exceed it and ollama silently truncates your prompt from the left. Override it with `num_ctx` in your options.

Temperature controls randomness. At `0.0`, ollama returns the highest-probability token every time — deterministic, useful for structured outputs like JSON. At `1.0+`, responses become creative but less reliable. For code generation, `0.1–0.3` is the sweet spot.

Top-p (nucleus sampling) works alongside temperature — ollama samples only from tokens whose cumulative probability exceeds `top_p`. Setting `top_p: 0.9` prunes the long tail of unlikely tokens. Top-k (`top_k: 40`) caps the candidate pool to the 40 most probable tokens before top-p applies.

These interact: low temperature + high top-p ≈ greedy; high temperature + low top-p ≈ constrained randomness. For RAG pipelines, `temperature: 0.1, top_p: 0.9, num_ctx: 8192` gives deterministic, context-aware output without hallucinating beyond the retrieved window.$escape$,
  $escape$import ollama

response = ollama.chat(
    model='llama3.2',
    messages=[{'role': 'user', 'content': 'Summarize this document: ...'}],
    options={
        'temperature': 0.1,
        'top_p': 0.9,
        'top_k': 40,
        'num_ctx': 8192,
        'num_predict': 512,
    }
)

print(response['message']['content'])$escape$,
  $escape$python$escape$,
